    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"7-32\">\n<h2>7-32</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 7, Section 5: Exponential Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Models simple and compound interest with equations and uses the model for long-term prediction.</div>\n<div><div><div><p>In the previous chapter you used models as an estimate of real behavior. Creating a linear model for scattered data gave you a mathematical way to describe the data and to make predictions.</p><p>Simple and compound interest in problem 7-31 were both <strong>step functions</strong>. Writing equations for step functions can be very complicated. However, we can model the step functions with other equations we are already familiar with.</p><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>Think about the growth and the starting point for the simple and compound interest situations from this lesson. Model each of the two step functions with an equation. Let <em>y</em>represent the money in the account after <em>$x$</em> years.</p></li><li><p>Check that your equation represents the tables in problem 7-30. If your models do not match the tables, correct your equation.</p></li><li><p>Use your model to predict how much your original \\$1000 investment would be worth at the end of $20$ years in the credit union.</p></li><li><p>Why are the equations considered a model, instead of a representation of the real behavior? Is there an advantage to using the model to make predictions?</p></li></ol></div><div></div></div></div>\n</section>",
