    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"7-33\">\n<h2>7-33</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 7, Section 5: Exponential Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Builds a quarterly compound-interest model using a periodic multiplier.</div>\n<div><div><div><p>From now on in this course, we will use continuous functions to model situations, unless indicated otherwise. <strong></strong></p><p>A third option for investing money is a money market account, which offers $8\\%$ annual interest <em>compounded quarterly</em> (four times per year). This means that the $8\\%$ is divided into four parts over the year, so the bank pays $2\\%$ every three months.</p><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>Model the value (every three months) of the \\$1000 investment in this money market account with an equation. Let <em>$y$</em>represent the money in the account after <em>$x$</em> quarters.</p></li><li><p>Use the model to find the value of your \\$1000 investment at four years. How does this compare with your other investment options from problem 7-30?</p></li></ol></div><div></div></div></div>\n</section>",
