    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"7-43\">\n<h2>7-43</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 7, Section 5: Exponential Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Graphs penny-lab data, describes decay behavior, estimates a multiplier, and writes an exponential model.</div>\n<div class=\"contentContainerReference-body\"><p class=\"\">Decide what your dependent and independent variables are for “The Penny Lab” data, clearly label them, and graph your data on your own graph paper. Then graph your data carefully on a team <a href=\"http://pdfs.cpm.org/stuRes/CCA/chapter_07/CCA%20Lesson%207.1.4%20RP.pdf\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">Lesson 7.1.4 Resource Page</a> obtained from your teacher or using the <a href=\"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/sbno1msb85\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><em>7-42 &amp; 7-43 eTool</em></a>. </p><p class=\"etool-note\">Interactive eTool referenced in original lesson.</p><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p class=\"\">Include your team’s data with those from other teams to present to the class. Then examine and describe the resulting scatterplot. Where does the graph cross the <em>$y$</em>-axis? Does the graph have any asymptotes? Should the graph be continuous or discrete?    </p></li><li><p class=\"\">Is this situation increasing or decreasing? What does this mean about the multiplier? Using what you know about the probability of flipping a fair coin, what would you expect or estimate the multiplier to be? </p></li><li><p class=\"\">Write an equation for an exponential function that models the data. Make sure you also write a “let” statement for your variables.  </p></li><li><p class=\"\">What output does your function give for <em>$x = 0$</em>? What could this mean in relation to the situation?   </p></li><li><p class=\"\">Could there be an output value for <em>$x = −1$</em>? If so, what might it mean?</p></li><li><p class=\"\">In the context of this situation, what should the domain of the model that you wrote in part (c) be? With the appropriate domain, what would a graph of your model look like? </p></li><li><p class=\"\">What family of functions that you saw in previous chapters has graphs like the one you made in part (f)? What are the first few values of this function? What is the equation?   </p></li></ol></div>\n</section>",
