    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"7-48\">\n<h2>7-48</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 7, Section 5: Exponential Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Models depreciation as exponential decay and interprets value over time.</div>\n<div class=\"contentContainerReference-body\"><p class=\"\">Assume that a DVD loses $60\\%$ of its value every year it is in a video store. Suppose the initial value of the DVD was $\\$80$. <a href=\"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/exqk6fjqvm\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><em><span></span></em></a><span> </span><a href=\"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/ej9iqgao77\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><em><span><span>7-48 HW eTool</span></span></em></a>  </p><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p class=\"\">What multiplier would you use to calculate the video’s new values?</p></li><li><p class=\"\">What is the value of the DVD after one year? After four years?</p></li><li><p class=\"\">Write a continuous function, <em>$V\\left(t\\right)$</em>, to model the value of a DVD after <em>$t$</em> years.</p></li><li><p class=\"\">When does the video have no value?</p></li><li><p class=\"\">Sketch a graph of this function. Be sure to scale and label the axes.</p></li></ol></div>\n</section>",
