    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-122\">\n<h2>11-122</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 7, Section 5: Exponential Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses exponential growth and exponential transformation models in a parade traffic-control context; image recreated.</div>\n<p><strong>TRAFFIC CONTROL</strong></p>\n<div class=\"visual-row\"><img alt=\"Traffic increasing before the parade.\" class=\"figure medium\" src=\"assets/11-122.png\"/></div>\n<p>Of course traffic will increase on the highways just before the parade. The Texas Highway Patrol uses the expected rate of traffic to decide how many officers to put on duty. Traffic is often measured in five-minute intervals. When an officer says $50$ vehicles passed by a certain place, the officer means that $50$ vehicles passed in a period of five minutes.</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>On a typical morning, $133$ vehicles pass the El Fiero León bridge. But starting at 8 a.m. on parade day, the traffic increases by $19\\%$ each hour. How many cars pass the bridge as the parade starts at 4 p.m.?</li><li>The Texas Highway Patrol uses the model $n=(1.005)^v$ to plan the number of officers on duty, where $v$ is the number of vehicles in five minutes and $n$ is the number of officers needed. How many officers should they have on duty at 4 p.m.? What is the percent increase of number of officers in the model?</li><li>The model in part (b) does not account for the rowdy behavior of partying out-of-towners. For celebrations like this, the Highway Patrol likes to adjust its model by what it calls the “$k$ factor.”<br/><br/>If the model in part (b) is called $f(v)$, which “$k$ factor” do you recommend the Highway Patrol uses for the Cinco de Mayo celebration: $f(v)+k$, $f(kv)$, $k\\cdot f(v)$, or $f(v+k)$? The Highway Patrol will use $k=3$ no matter which transformation they use. Explain your choice.</li></ol>\n</section>",
