    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-124\">\n<h2>11-124</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 7, Section 5: Exponential Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses sparse contextual data to choose a model type and make an extrapolated prediction; table preserved.</div>\n<p><strong>TACOS</strong></p><p>There are fifteen Taco Shacks along the parade route. People wait in long lines to get their famed tacos. The food director needs to predict how many tacos will be sold so that he can purchase enough supplies. Looking back at the last five years, this was all the director could find from previous Cinco de Mayo celebrations:</p>\n<table class=\"data\"><tr><th>Time of Day</th><th># Tacos Sold<br/>That Hour</th></tr><tr><td>8 a.m.</td><td>1150</td></tr><tr><td>Noon</td><td>2257</td></tr><tr><td>10 a.m.</td><td>1512</td></tr><tr><td>Noon</td><td>2091</td></tr><tr><td>8 a.m.</td><td>954</td></tr></table>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>Based on what you have already learned about the celebration, what type of function should the food director use to model the number of tacos sold each hour?</li><li>Predict the number of tacos sold in the 7 p.m. hour. Justify your prediction to the satisfaction of the food director.</li><li>What concern do you have about the prediction you made?</li></ol>\n</section>",
